1. What is DSP?
   Digital Signal Processing is the analysis and processing of signals using digital methods.

2. What is sampling?
   Sampling is converting a continuous-time signal into discrete values at regular intervals.

3. What is sampling frequency?
   Number of samples taken per second.

4. What is Nyquist rate?
   Twice the highest frequency present in the signal.

5. What happens if sampling frequency is too low?
   Aliasing occurs.

6. What is aliasing?
   High-frequency components appear as false lower frequencies after sampling.

7. What is DFT?
   Discrete Fourier Transform converts a signal from time domain to frequency domain.

8. Why do we use FFT?
   FFT is a faster method to compute DFT.

9. What does magnitude spectrum show?
   It shows the strength of frequency components.

10. Why did the 1 second signal give a cleaner spectrum?
    Because it contained an integer number of cycles.

11. What is spectral leakage?
    Spreading of signal energy into nearby frequency bins.

12. Why does leakage occur?
    Because of non-integer number of cycles in the observation window.

13. Why is Hamming window used?
    To reduce spectral leakage.

14. What is a window function?
    A function used to taper signal edges before FFT.

15. What is white noise?
    Random noise containing many frequency components.

16. What is smoothing filter?
    A filter used to reduce rapid random noise variations.

17. What is a moving average filter?
    A filter that averages nearby samples.

18. Why was a 6-point filter used?
    To smooth the noisy signal by averaging 6 samples.

19. What is convolution?
    A mathematical operation used to apply a filter to a signal.

20. Why use convolution in filtering?
    Because output of an LTI system is input convolved with impulse response.

21. What is impulse response?
    Output of a system when input is a unit impulse.

22. What is FIR filter?
    Finite Impulse Response filter with finite number of coefficients.

23. Why FIR filters are preferred?
    They are stable and can provide linear phase.

24. What is cutoff frequency?
    Frequency where filter starts reducing the signal.

25. What is low-pass filter?
    A filter that passes low frequencies and attenuates high frequencies.

26. Why was 20 Hz cutoff chosen?
    To pass 10 Hz signal and remove 100 Hz noise.

27. What is Hamming window in FIR design?
    A window used to reduce side lobes and ripple.

28. What happens if filter length increases?
    Sharper response but more delay and computation.

29. What is autocorrelation?
    Correlation of a signal with itself.

30. What is cross-correlation?
    Correlation between two different signals.

31. Why use cross-correlation?
    To find similarity or delay between signals.

32. How was delay found in experiment?
    From the peak position of correlation.

33. Why autocorrelation peak is maximum at zero lag?
    Because signal matches itself perfectly.

34. Why sine and square wave correlation was noticeable?
    Because both had same frequency.

35. Why sine 10 Hz and sine 20 Hz had low correlation?
    Because frequencies were different.

36. What is lag in correlation?
    Shift amount between two signals.

37. Why only positive half of FFT was plotted?
    Because FFT of real signals is symmetric.

38. What is phase response?
    Shows phase shift introduced by the filter.

39. What is magnitude response?
    Shows how much each frequency is passed or attenuated.

40. What is linear phase?
    All frequency components are delayed equally.
41. What is a discrete-time signal?
    A signal defined only at specific sample points.

42. What is a continuous-time signal?
    A signal defined for every instant of time.

43. What is quantization?
    Converting signal amplitudes into finite digital levels.

44. What is quantization error?
    Difference between actual value and quantized value.

45. What is resolution in ADC?
    Smallest amplitude change an ADC can detect.

46. What is ADC?
    Analog to Digital Converter.

47. What is DAC?
    Digital to Analog Converter.

48. What is time domain representation?
    Signal shown as amplitude versus time.

49. What is frequency domain representation?
    Signal shown as amplitude versus frequency.

50. Why is frequency domain useful?
    It helps identify frequency components easily.

51. What is a sinusoidal signal?
    A periodic signal in sine or cosine form.

52. What is amplitude of a signal?
    Maximum value of the signal.

53. What is period of a signal?
    Time taken to complete one cycle.

54. What is frequency of a signal?
    Number of cycles per second.

55. Relation between frequency and period?
    Frequency = 1 / Period.

56. What is phase of a signal?
    Angular shift of a waveform.

57. What is angular frequency?
    2πf radians per second.

58. What is fundamental frequency?
    Lowest frequency of a periodic signal.

59. What is harmonic?
    Integer multiple of the fundamental frequency.

60. Why does square wave contain harmonics?
    Because it is non-sinusoidal.

61. What is random noise?
    Unwanted unpredictable disturbance in a signal.

62. What is Gaussian noise?
    Noise with normal probability distribution.

63. What is SNR?
    Signal-to-noise ratio.

64. High SNR means what?
    Signal is stronger than noise.

65. Low SNR means what?
    Noise is high compared to signal.

66. What is passband?
    Frequency range allowed through the filter.

67. What is stopband?
    Frequency range strongly attenuated by the filter.

68. What is transition band?
    Region between passband and stopband.

69. What is attenuation?
    Reduction in signal magnitude.

70. What is gain?
    Amplification factor of a system.

71. What is unity gain?
    Gain equal to 1.

72. What is normalization of frequency?
    Expressing frequency relative to sampling frequency.

73. What is zero padding?
    Adding zeros to a signal before FFT.

74. Why use zero padding?
    To improve FFT display resolution.

75. Does zero padding add information?
    No, it only improves visual resolution.

76. What is FFT bin?
    A discrete frequency location in FFT output.

77. What determines FFT resolution?
    Sampling frequency divided by number of samples.

78. What is leakage reduction method?
    Using window functions.

79. Name common windows.
    Rectangular, Hamming, Hann, Blackman.

80. Which window has lower ripple than rectangular?
    Hamming window.

81. What is side lobe?
    Small unwanted peaks beside main lobe in spectrum.

82. What is main lobe?
    Central peak of a window spectrum.

83. Why are side lobes undesirable?
    They cause leakage to nearby frequencies.

84. What is ripple in filter response?
    Small oscillations in passband or stopband.

85. What is ideal low-pass filter?
    Passes all low frequencies and blocks all high frequencies perfectly.

86. Is ideal filter practical?
    No, it requires infinite impulse response.

87. Why use practical FIR filter?
    It is stable and implementable.

88. What is filter order?
    Related to number of coefficients in filter.

89. Higher order filter means what?
    Sharper frequency response.

90. What is delay in FIR filter?
    Time shift introduced by the filter.

91. What is group delay?
    Average delay of signal components.

92. What is symmetric impulse response?
    Coefficients mirror around center.

93. Symmetric FIR gives what benefit?
    Linear phase response.

94. What is causal system?
    Output depends only on present and past inputs.

95. What is stable system?
    Bounded input gives bounded output.

96. What is LTI system?
    Linear Time Invariant system.

97. Why are LTI systems important?
    They are easy to analyze using convolution and frequency response.

98. What is energy signal?
    Signal with finite total energy.

99. What is power signal?
    Signal with finite average power.

100. Why is DSP important in real life?
     Used in audio, image processing, communication, radar, biomedical systems.
